Solution. By the condition $\mathrm{t}=\mathrm{r}-\sqrt{2}$, where $\mathrm{r}$ is a rational number. Then

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathrm{t}^{3}+\sqrt{2}=(\mathrm{r}-\sqrt{2})^{3}=\mathrm{r}^{3}-3 \mathrm{r}^{2} \sqrt{2}+3 \mathrm{r}(\sqrt{2})^{2}-(\sqrt{2})^{3}+\sqrt{2}= \\
& =r^{3}+6 \mathrm{r}-\left(3 \mathrm{r}^{2}+1\right) \cdot \sqrt{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

If this number (denote it as $\mathrm{R}$) turned out to be rational, then $\sqrt{2}$ would be a rational number

$$
\sqrt{2}=\frac{r^{3}+6 r-R}{3 r^{2}+1}
$$

which, as is known, is not the case.

【Analysis】According to the problem, these are three consecutive natural numbers. Since $7, 8, 9$ are also consecutive natural numbers, we first find the least common multiple (LCM) of $7, 8, 9$: $7 \times 8 \times 9=504$. Then, subtracting 9 results in a multiple of 9, subtracting 8 results in a multiple of 8, and subtracting 7 results in a multiple of 7, yielding $495, 496, 497$ as the numbers that meet the criteria.

【Solution】The least common multiple of $7, 8, 9$ is: $7 \times 8 \times 9=504$;
$$
\begin{array}{l}
504-7=497, \\
504-8=496,
\end{array}
$$
$$
\begin{array}{l}
504-9=495 ; \\
495+496+497=1488 .
\end{array}
$$

Therefore, the answer is: 1488.
